******
[1] Hong Kong, Macau
Date: 24 Sep 2008
Source: Sydney Morning Herald [edited]
<http://news.smh.com.au/world/three-more-hospitalised-in-milk-scandal-20080924-4mp8.html>


Three more children outside mainland China have developed kidney
stones after drinking Chinese-made milk products in a scandal over
tainted milk blamed for 4 infant deaths.

At least 8 Asian countries have banned or restricted Chinese dairy
products. The European Union has urged customs authorities throughout
the bloc to keep a closer eye on food imports from China.

The 2 new cases in Hong Kong and one in Macau bring the total number
of cases outside mainland China to 5. In the mainland, some 54 000
have fallen ill, as well as the 4 who died.

A 16-month-old infant in China's southern enclave of Macau was
diagnosed after being fed Nestle milk powder made in China's
northeastern Heilongjiang province, the Macau government said.

However, no government tests have found melamine, the industrial
chemical at the heart of the scandal, in Nestle milk products.

Switzerland-based Nestle said in a statement that its milk products
sold in China and Hong Kong are "absolutely safe" and that none are
made from tainted milk.

Two boys aged 2 and 9 in Hong Kong were in a stable condition, the
Hong Kong government said.

A senior Chinese official has pledged to crack down on a nationwide
milk-gathering system that he conceded was "out of control".

Chinese Agriculture Minister Sun Zhengcai told a meeting with the
health and public security ministries that the industrial chemical
melamine was likely added at stations that collect milk from small
individual dairy farmers.

"We must crack down on them with the greatest determination and the
toughest measures," Sun said in a meeting held late Monday [22 Sep
2008], but reported on the ministry's website.

The government has been scrambling for days to show it is tackling
the problem. Recent days have seen a number of arrests and forced
resignations of officials over the widening scandal.

The company at the centre of the scandal, Sanlu Group Co, had no
comment about allegations it had 1st received complaints more than 8
months ago about its infant formula.

A deeply shaken dairy industry pledged to reform itself. A group of
316 Chinese milk producers and retailers issued a joint statement
promising to keep the dairy industry clean, take responsibility for
product quality, and take concrete action to satisfy consumers, state
broadcaster CCTV said.

Melamine, used to make plastics and fertilizer, has been found in
infant formula and other milk products from 22 Chinese dairy
companies. Suppliers trying to cut costs are believed to have added
it to watered-down milk because its high nitrogen content masks the
resulting protein deficiency.

Taiwan's Premier Liu Chao-shiuan said the island would send a team of
experts to mainland China to probe the extent of the crisis. Taiwan
has imported 25 tons of tainted baby products made by Sanlu Group.

The World Health Organisation has warned of possible smuggling of the
infant formula across borders.

The scandal has claimed the head of Li Changjiang, who stepped down
on Monday [22 Sep 2008] as boss of the General Administration of
Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine. Li had run the safety
watchdog since 2001, and his resignation comes a year after he and
the government promised to overhaul the system in response to a
series of product safety scares.

New regulations and procedures were introduced in an attempt to
restore consumer confidence and preserve export markets after a
string of recalls involving tainted toothpaste, faulty tires,
contaminated seafood and pet food.

Baby formula and other milk products have been pulled from stores
around the country, and Chinese dairy products have been recalled or
banned in Japan, Singapore, Brunei, Malaysia and Hong Kong.

One of China's biggest milk producers, China Mengniu Dairy Co, saw
its stock price plummet slightly more than 60 per cent in Hong Kong
trading after some of its products were found tainted with melamine.

--
