[2] Hong Kong - Melamine found in cakes, new cases
Date: 24 Sep 2008
Source: The Standard [edited]
<http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=72114&sid=20706729&con_type=1>


The number of Hong Kong children found with kidney stones rose to 4
as the industrial chemical melamine believed to be responsible was
found in cakes for the 1st time.

In addition, 365 children have been referred to special assessment
centers after displaying symptoms related to kidney problems.

The Centre for Food Safety said tests on Four Seas Cake (strawberry
flavor) showed more than twice the permitted amount that became
effective yesterday [23 Sep 2008]. The chemical was also found in
White Rabbit Creamy Candies.

The center urged the public to stop consuming these items and said
importers had agreed to recall the products. A spokesman said no one
will be prosecuted since the samples were collected before the
amendment setting the melamine limit at 2.6 parts per million for
non-dairy products came into effect.

The 2 new kidney patients, aged 9 years and 29 months, were living in
the mainland.

The 9-year-old, who has been drinking 2 to 4 packets of Mengniu milk
(250g) purchased in Shenzhen everyday for the past 4 years, was
admitted to a private hospital in Hong Kong last Saturday [20 Sep
2008]. He has since been discharged and is now in stable condition.

The 29-month-old boy had been drinking Sanlu and Yili milk since he
was 8 months old. He was examined at Kwong Wah Hospital outpatient
clinic on Monday [22 Sep 2008] and remains under treatment.

About one-quarter of the 1328 children seeking evaluations at the 18
general outpatient clinics yesterday [23 Sep 2008] were referred to
the 7 special assessment centers for further checkups after
displaying symptoms related to kidney problems.

None of the children, however, required hospital admission.

The symptoms involved blood in the urine, a small amount of
urination, discomfort when urinating or bad temper.

Secretary for Food and Health York Chow Yat-ngok said a task force
will study the number of Hong Kong-born children living in the mainland.

The center hotline, 2125 1133, has received 2148 inquiries, with 651
callers claiming they or their children had consumed tainted milk
products. Of these, 157 claimed to have symptoms of renal problems.

A 16-month-old child in Macau, who was fed Nestle milk powder, has
been diagnosed with a kidney stone.

[Byline: Nickkita Lau]

--
