[3] Taiwan - possible cases
Date: 24 Sep 2008
Source: Taiwan News Online [edited]
<http://www.etaiwannews.com/etn/news_content.php?id=747325>


A 2-year-old girl who lived in China with her parents was diagnosed
with signs of a hardening kidney yesterday [23 Sep 2008] in what
might be the 1st case in Taiwan of a melamine-related disease.

The girl drank milk made from Chinese milk powder on a regular basis
as she lived with her Taiwanese father and Chinese mother in
Guangzhou, the Chinese-language United Evening News said yesterday
[23 Sep 2008].

The family recently arrived in Taiwan and had the girl undergo a
regular check at a hospital in Taichung County.

Doctors found a hardening kidney, though no kidney stone, symptoms of
ingesting melamine, the toxic chemical added to some Chinese dairy
products to fool protein tests.

The hospital said continued observation of the child was necessary,
though kidney stones would not necessarily develop. Another medical
test would be needed 2 months from now, the hospital said.

People needed to drink the tainted product for at least 2 months
before kidney problems would show, Taipei City Hospital president
Huang Pi-tao told reporters.

In Taipei, doctors found kidney stones in 2 adults out of 25 adults
and 2 children who underwent checks yesterday [23 Sep 2008] morning.
The doctors were also unable to tell whether the kidney problems were
related to long-term drinking of milk products.

A 74-year-old man who said he had the habit of drinking milk tea was
diagnosed with a 2-centimeter-long kidney stone. Doctors said he
should undergo an operation to remove the stone.

The other patient, a 40-year-old woman, was in a far less serious
state. Her problem could be solved by drinking more water, doctors said.

The diagnoses came as hospitals across Taiwan geared up to provide
free kidney-stone screening for children or for patients who thought
they might have suffered from drinking the contaminated dairy
products. The hospitals taking part in the 6-month program will
provide urine tests and ultrasound examinations.

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[The above newswire mentions the identification of possible renal
disease in a 2-year old with a history of ingestion of milk prepared
from powdered milk while living in Guangdong. It also mentions that
kidney stones were identified in 2 out of 25 adults screened and 2
children screened. It seems to suggest that there were now 3 cases of
kidney abnormalities in children identified in Taiwan. Concluding
that the kidney stones in adults were related to ingestion of
melamine adulterated milk products will be a challenge, unless these
individuals are screened for the presence of melamine and its
by-products. - Mod.MPP]

******
[4] Viet Nam - melamine found in milk products
Date: Wed 24 Sep 2008
Source: Thanh Nien News [edited]
<http://www.thanhniennews.com/healthy/?catid=8&newsid=42265>


Tests conducted in Ho Chi Minh City show the presence of melamine in
samples taken from milk imported from YiLi Industrial Group, one of 3
Chinese companies found to have melamine in their milk products.

Local importer Kim An Company in HCMCs Phu Nhuan District said
results from examinations done by an affiliate of the city's
Department of Science and Technology revealed a melamine
concentration of 25.34 micrograms per liter.

However, no regulations have been established in Viet Nam that
pronounce at what concentration level melamine would be poisonous for
consumption.

Kim An Company also said it has recalled all the YiLi milk it had
distributed. However, 321 tins of one-liter milk had already been
sold. The company reportedly imported 1494 cartons of milk (one
carton contains 12 tins) from YiLi Industrial Group.

The HCMC Health Department said Tuesday [23 Sep 2008] it had
confiscated 1081 cartons from the company and also seized 3375
kilograms of milk powder lacking required documents being transported
on a truck belonging to Duc Long Hang Co., Ltd. in District 10.

An inspection in Hanoi Tuesday [23 Sep 2008] of Hoang Lam Trading and
Technology JSC found 25 tons of cream imported from China lacking
quality certification.

The inspectors requested the company present documents today [24 Sep
2008] on 42 tons of milk powder imported from China last year [2007]
without quality guarantees.

Deputy Minister of Health Cao Minh Quang Tuesday [23 Sep 2008] set up
2 inspection forces to probe production and trading of dairy products
in northern and southern provinces.

In related news, Sanlu Group, the Chinese dairy firm 1st found to be
selling melamine-contaminated goods, allegedly began receiving
complaints of sick children as early as last December [2007], AFP
quoted Chinese media CCTV as saying.

The media source also said local officials in the northern city of
Shijiazhuang, where Sanlu is based, delayed referring the matter to
higher authorities for more than a month after Sanlu informed them of
the problem on [2 Aug 2008].

[Byline: Thanh Tung, Nam Son]

