*****
[5] Viet Nam - melamine found in milk products
Date: Tue 23 Sep 2008
Source: Nhan Dan [edited]
<http://www.nhandan.com.vn/english/life/230908/life_m.htm>


The Health Ministry has sent an urgent message to centrally-governed
provinces and cities to suspend the circulation of milk products and
materials of unidentified origins.

The ministry also directed local health departments to work with
related agencies to inspect the sources of supply of all milk
products and materials in the market, especially those imported from China.

Qualitative samples taken from Vietnamese and imported milk products
and materials must be tested for melamine, with test results being
reported to the Health Ministry immediately.

Provinces and cities were asked to submit preliminary reports to the
Health Ministry prior to [25 Sep 2008].

On [22 Sep 2008], Ho Chi Minh City's Health Department Inspector
sealed up 18 000 liters of Yili Pure Milk produced by the Chinese
Inner Mongolia Yili Industrial Group at the warehouse of an importing company.

Noticeably, this is one of 22 Chinese companies whose product samples
were found to be melamine-contaminated.

Samples of 18 000 liters of Yili Pure Milk were taken for testing for
melamine, a chemical substance which causes kidney-related diseases
in many Chinese children.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MBDS <promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Milk products imported from China have been confiscated in Viet Nam,
as they were found to be contaminated with melamine, which has
adverse effects on the function of kidneys, and can lead to renal
failure. However, some of those products have already been sold. At
present, there have been no case reports of children with kidney
stones or kidney failure in Viet Nam associated with the
melamine-adulterated milk.

China has been reporting an increasing number of children who have
sought medical treatment associated with the consumption of
melamine-contaminated powdered infant formula. According to the
report from the Ministry of Health of China dated 22 Sep 2008, nearly
40 000 children have received medical treatment; almost 12 900 are
currently hospitalized, and 3 deaths have been confirmed (see prior
PRO/MBDS posting Infant kidney stones - China (06): WHO, timeline
20080922.2990 below).

Background information on melamine at the Epidemic and Pandemic Alert
and Response of the World Health Organization is available at:
<http://www.who.int/csr/media/faq/QAmelamine/en/index.html>.

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg> and
<http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Viet Nam can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=14.9,108.5,5>.
This map shows other outbreaks in Viet Nam and surrounding countries
that have been reported on ProMED-mail. The postings can be directly
accessed through this map. - Mod.YMA]

