Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS <promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[As of today, 24 Sep 2008, there have been 5 cases of children
identified with renal stones associated with ingestion of implicated
Chinese milk products outside of mainland China: 4 residents of Hong
Kong and one resident of Macau. There is the suggestion of between
one and 3 possible cases identified in Taiwan as well (see part [3]
above) and rumors of cases in the Maldives (see part [6][a] above).
From the myriad newswires available, the list of countries with
identifiable products containing the implicated Chinese milk
continues to grow. It is clear that with time, more and more
countries will be announcing either bans on importations of food
products known to contain Chinese milk or will be implementing
regulations that mandate testing imported products for melamine
before permitting them to be sold in their countries. A real
challenge will be to establish whether there are other children
affected by these products in other countries where the products were imported.

ProMED-mail will continue to monitor the situation and provide
updates when more information is known on the extent of the impact of
the melamine adulteration. At this point, further information on
additional countries banning importation seems unnecessary, as the
pattern is clearly established this is occurring in many countries. - Mod.MPP]
